## Task 6: Text and Font

**Styling Text and Fonts in CSS**

CSS provides various properties to control the appearance of text and fonts on a web page. Here are some common properties and their uses:

* **font-family:** Specifies the font family to be used.
* **font-size:** Sets the size of the font.
* **font-weight:** Defines the boldness of the font (e.g., normal, bold, bolder).
* **text-align:** Aligns the text within an element (e.g., left, center, right).
* **color:** Sets the color of the text.
* **text-decoration:** Applies decorations to text (e.g., underline, line-through).
* **text-transform:** Changes the capitalization of text (e.g., uppercase, lowercase).

**Example:**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Text and Font Styling</title>
    <style>
        h1 {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            font-size: 36px;
            font-weight: bold;
            text-align: center;
        }

        p {
            font-size: 16px;
            line-height: 1.5;
            color: #666;
        }

        a {
            color: blue;
            text-decoration: underline;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>This is a Heading</h1>
    <p>This is a paragraph of text.</p>
    <p>This is another paragraph.</p>
    <a href="https://example.com">Link to Example</a>
</body>
</html>
```

**Explanation:**

- The `h1` element is styled with Arial font, 36px size, bold weight, and centered alignment.
- The `p` elements are styled with a font size of 16px, line height of 1.5, and a gray color.
- The `a` element is styled with blue text and an underline decoration.

By using these properties, you can customize the appearance of text and fonts to match the desired style of your web page.
